						               													<description>Six horse owners get together annually to race their best thoroughbreds &amp;ndash; for a little money, but mainly for bragging rights. There are three races and three strict bets. The most money wins.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Unlike similar table-top games, in Big Time the luck element is minimized. Sure, you&amp;rsquo;ll have a &amp;ldquo;stable&amp;rdquo; of horses, but you won&amp;rsquo;t roll dice and check your horse card to see how far your steed goes. And you won&amp;rsquo;t spend your time making multiple bets on which horse will win the race, either. What you will do is focus on the race itself, and your share of the purse&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Big Time Horse Racing is a thinking person&amp;rsquo;s game. The types of horses in a race, the length of the race, post position and how the race will be run are the important factors. On each turn, players will carefully choose a card to play from their hands &amp;ndash; but only one card will determine the results which will apply to all the horses on the racetrack. Sometimes you&amp;rsquo;ll want your card to be chosen, and sometimes you won&amp;rsquo;t. Sometimes you&amp;rsquo;ll try to hinder other players instead of helping yourself. Sometimes you&amp;rsquo;ll benefit all horses of your type, and sometimes you&amp;rsquo;ll selfishly give yourself a bonus at the expense of those horses.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;You&amp;rsquo;ll also have to decide when to hold your horse back, when to &amp;ldquo;make your move,&amp;rdquo; what to do in the turns, and even if you&amp;rsquo;ll hand the race to an opponent if you can&amp;rsquo;t finish in the money. There is betting, but it&amp;rsquo;s limited, and thought will be required here, too &amp;ndash; if you want to win the day!&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;mdash;description from the designer&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
